{
  "text": "The onset of rash is early, generally developing over a period of six weeks after starting treatment [CITATION_1] . The first week is characterized by sensory disturbance, erythema, and edema, followed by papulopustular eruption during the second week. Crusting appears by Week 4. If treated successfully, the papulopustular eruptions disappear and make way for erythema and dry skin by Week 6. In some cases, the rash may improve spontaneously [CITATION_2] , but may also persist [CITATION_3] . Phase I escalation studies have shown the rash to be dose-dependant [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] .",
